<!-- What Is Business Valuation -->
<div class="service-section">
<h2>What Is Business Valuation?</h2>
<p>Business valuation is the process of determining the economic value of a business, professional practice, or ownership interest. As a certified valuation expert, I use recognized methodologies to establish defensible values for closely-held businesses, partnership interests, and professional practices. Business valuation provides the foundation for resolving disputes in litigation, divorce proceedings, shareholder conflicts, and estate matters throughout Rhode Island and New England.</p>
<p>With extensive experience in vocational rehabilitation and forensic economics, I bring a unique perspective as a valuation analyst, particularly in cases involving professional practices, service businesses, and companies where key-person issues affect value. My analyses address both economic value and the human capital factors that drive business performance, providing attorneys with comprehensive litigation support.</p>
</div>
<!-- When Is Business Valuation Needed -->
<div class="service-section">
<h2>When Is Business Valuation Needed?</h2>
<p>Business valuation expert services are essential in numerous legal contexts:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Divorce and Marital Dissolution:</strong> Determining the value of business interests for equitable distribution</li>
<li><strong>Shareholder Disputes:</strong> Valuing minority interests in oppression and dissent cases</li>
<li><strong>Partnership Dissolution:</strong> Establishing buyout values and resolving deadlock situations</li>
<li><strong>Estate and Gift Tax Planning:</strong> Supporting attorneys with IRS-compliant valuations</li>
<li><strong>Commercial Litigation:</strong> Quantifying business damages and lost profits</li>
<li><strong>Buy-Sell Agreements:</strong> Interpreting and applying valuation formulas</li>
</ul>
<p>Rhode Island attorneys rely on my business valuation expertise to provide clarity in complex financial matters, ensuring fair outcomes for their clients.</p>
</div>
<!-- How Our Valuations Support Your Case -->
<div class="service-section">
<h2>How Our Valuations Support Your Case</h2>
<p>As your business valuation expert, I employ the three standard approaches to business valuation, selecting the most appropriate methods based on the business type, available data, and litigation requirements. My valuation analyst methodology ensures defensible conclusions that support your case strategy.</p>
<h3>Income Approach</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Discounted Cash Flow (DCF):</strong> Projecting future cash flows and discounting to present value</li>
<li><strong>Capitalized Earnings:</strong> Capitalizing normalized earnings for stable businesses</li>
<li><strong>Excess Earnings Method:</strong> Appropriate for asset-intensive businesses</li>
</ul>
<h3>Market Approach</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Guideline Company Method:</strong> Comparison to publicly traded companies</li>
<li><strong>Guideline Transaction Method:</strong> Analysis of comparable business sales</li>
<li><strong>Rules of Thumb:</strong> Industry-specific valuation multiples when appropriate</li>
</ul>
<h3>Asset Approach</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Net Asset Value:</strong> Adjusted book value approach</li>
<li><strong>Liquidation Value:</strong> For distressed or dissolving businesses</li>
<li><strong>Replacement Cost:</strong> For asset-heavy operations</li>
</ul>
</div>
